'''''Match Day''''' is an [[association football]] [[video game]] franchise created by [[Jon Ritman]] in [[1984 in video gaming|1984]] for the [[Home computer#1980s|1980s 8-bit home computer]] market.

== Games in the series ==

The following games are part of the '''Match Day series'''. All of the games were published by [[Ocean Software|Ocean]], with the exception of ''Super Match Soccer'':

* ''[[Match Day (video game)|Match Day]]'': the first game in the series. It was created in [[1984 in video gaming|1984]] and released on most home computers of the era, but is most well known for its Sinclair Spectrum incarnation. It was designed and developed by [[Jon Ritman]] with the help of [[Chris Clarke (programmer)|Chris Clarke]].<ref>[http://www.gamasutra.com/php-bin/news_index.php?story=12762 Playing Catch Up: Match Day's Jon Ritman] at Gamasutra.com</ref>
* ''International Match Day'' is an improved version of ''Match Day'' published in 1986 for the [[ZX Spectrum#ZX_Spectrum_128|ZX Spectrum 128]] with better sound and some full screen images.
* ''[[Match Day II]]'' was released in [[1987 in video gaming|1987]] for the [[Amstrad CPC]], [[ZX Spectrum]], [[MSX]] and [[Commodore 64]] platforms. It was written by [[Jon Ritman]], with graphics by [[Bernie Drummond]] and music and sound by [[Guy Stevens (videogame programmer)|Guy Stevens]]<ref>[http://www.jonritman.f2s.com/games/md2/index.htm Comment about authors of the game in Ritman's home page, ritman.co.uk]</ref> (Commodore version, programmed by [[John Darnel]]<ref>[http://www.c64.com/interviews/galway.html Martin Galway interview] at c64.com</ref>). The game was the first one to include complete control over ball direction, power and elevation (using a kickometer<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20000516151934/http://www.geocities.com/SiliconValley/Heights/5874/footy.htm Football games] at geocities.com/SiliconValley</ref>), and a brand new deflection system (Diamond Deflection System).<ref>[http://www.ysrnry.co.uk/articles/matchdayii.htm Matchday 2 review] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080221113802/http://www.ysrnry.co.uk/articles/matchdayii.htm |date=2008-02-21 }} at Your Sinclair Rock and Roll Years</ref>
* ''Final Whistle'' was the name of an [[arcade machine]] very similar to ''Match Day 2'' (it was previously called ''Soccerama'' during development). Although it was finished it was never released.<ref>[http://perso.wanadoo.es/amstradcpc/interviews/ritman.html Interviews: Jon Ritman, a genius in play] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090607085726/http://perso.wanadoo.es/amstradcpc/interviews/ritman.html |date=2009-06-07 }} at amstradmuseum.com</ref>
* ''[[Super Match Soccer]]'', was released in [[1998 in video gaming|1998]] by [[Acclaim Entertainment|Acclaim]]. Although its working title was ''The Net'',<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20000301193720/http://www.geocities.com/TimesSquare/Battlefield/8875/jritman.html Interview with Jon Ritman] at TimesSquare/Battlefield (through archive.org)</ref> it was intended to be released as ''Match Day III'' (it was even presented as such in a [[PlayStation (console)|PlayStation]]<ref>[http://www.absolute-PlayStation.com/api_preview/pmatch3.htm Match Day 3 preview] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110726065833/http://www.absolute-playstation.com/api_preview/pmatch3.htm |date=2011-07-26 }} at absolute-PlayStation.com</ref> preview in Spain), but due to licensing problems the name was finally changed. It was developed in 1998 by Cranberry Source and published by [[Acclaim Entertainment|Acclaim]].<ref>[http://www.gamefaqs.com/console/psx/data/573890.html Super Match Soccer] at gamefaqs.com</ref> The game is available for [[Personal computer|PC]] and [[PlayStation (console)|PlayStation]].<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20020613023139/http://pc.ign.com/objects/003/003888.html Super Match Soccer] at pc.ign.com</ref>

